The doc-module for `script/declarations_diff.sh` contains some details about this script.

Currently, this work is moved to a fork repo. https://github.com/jjdishere/mathlib4_stacks_project_field_new/tree/stacks_project_tag
After the whole chapter is tagged, we will submit this PR.
After the infrastructure `@[stacks]` mentioned in https://leanprover.zulipchat.com/#narrow/stream/113488-general/topic/stacks.20tags is finished, we will use this infrastructure.

Thanks a lot (to all the co-authors) for doing this! Hope there are more to come :)
I think I have gone through all the tags and the PR looks good to me modulo the two open comments.
Thank you @erdOne for reviewing this PR and checking all the tags carefully!
maintainer merge
Pull request has been placed on the maintainer queue by erdOne.
bors merge
Gone through the second half.

```suggestion
@[stacks 0BIJ "This is a special case of 0BIJ norm, we require separability here. "]
```
I'm confused by the purpose of the text after `@[stacks]`. Sometimes it is used to describe the difference from the stacks result and ours but I'm not sure what it's for here.

I think we should use it to describe the difference. But there are many kinds of differences. The difference in naming, in content (the mathlib theorem is only a part of theorem in stacks project) and in hypothesis.
I don't think this tag is right.

I see. This lemma corresponds to the content written in the small paragraph right following 09H5.

```
The separable degree of P always divides the degree and the quotient is a power of the characteristic. If the characteristic is zero, then degs(P)=deg(P).
```

There is no tag in Stacks Project for this small paragraph. I'll just remove this tag.
I don't think this tag is right.
Same as above.

```suggestion

/-- Any ring homomorphism `f : F  R` from a `DivisionRing F` to nonzero ring `R` is injective.
```
I think either 02JJ or 00GM is more suitable here.
Thanks! Fixed!
I don't think this tag is right.

Again, this corresponds to the first paragraph 

To get started, let us begin by providing several examples of fields. The reader should recall that if R is a ring and IR an ideal, then R/I is a field precisely when I is a maximal ideal.

in section 09FF. This tag is for the whole section. I'll delete this tag.
I don't think this tag is right.
Thanks! This is the discriminant of an element with respect to a certain basis. The discriminant of a field should its value when a = 1. Or more precisely, its image in `K/(K^*)^2`.
Removed.
I think this tag is a bit farfetched.
I agree. Removed.
I don't think this tag is right.

I believe this theorem aligns with the first sentence `A finite extension is algebraic.` of the 09GG statement.

A finite extension is algebraic. In fact, an extension E/k is algebraic if and only if every subextension k()/k generated by some E is finite.

I'll add a comment saying it is the first part.
I don't think this tag is right.
Thanks. Removed.
Is this the second part? The second part seems to be defining what finite extensions are.
Thanks! Removed.

```suggestion
@[stacks 09HK "Part 1, `finSepDegree` variant"]
```

```suggestion
separable closure of `F` in `E` if and only if `E` is purely inseparable over it. -/
@[stacks 030K "This theorem implies the `E/E_sep`  is purely inseparable part." -/
```

```suggestion
minimal polynomial over `K` is separable. Note that the minimal polynomial of any element not
integral over `F` is defined to be `0`, which is not a separable polynomial.
-/
@[stacks 09H1 "second part"]
```

```suggestion
@[to_additive isAddCyclic_of_card_nsmul_eq_zero_le, stacks 09HX "This theorem is stronger than \
09HX. It removes the abelian condition, and requires only `` instead of `=`."]
```
This is 09HJ instead.
Thanks! Nice catch!
I'm not sure if this is preferred.

I'll follow the original author's style at the beginning. If the author uses 
```
/-- foo
```
then it should be
```
bar. -/
```
If the author uses
```
/--
foo
```
then it should be
```
bar.
-/
```
The inconsistency here is caused by we originally wrote Stacks links in the comments. When we changed to the stacks attribute, we didn't delete the line breaks correctly.

```suggestion
```
I don't think this tag is right.

Thanks. Again, this is stated in the paragraph right following 030L.

Of course in characteristic 0 we have [E:F]=[E:F]s and [E:F]i=1. By multiplicativity (Lemma [09G9](https://stacks.math.columbia.edu/tag/09G9)) we have
[E:F]=[E:F]s[E:F]i
even in case some of these degrees are infinite. In fact, the separable degree and the inseparable degree are multiplicative too (see Lemma [09HK](https://stacks.math.columbia.edu/tag/09HK)).

Removed.
I don't think this tag is right.
Thanks. This is typo. This should be `0EXK`.
Fixed.

```suggestion
over `K`. -/
```

```suggestion
if and only if it is separable over `F`. -/
```

```suggestion
@[stacks 09H3 "Here we only require `f` splits instead of `K` is algebraically closed."]
```
I don't think this tag is right.
Thank you! Removed.

```suggestion
@[stacks 030L "Part 3, ``-valued variant"]
```

I don't thinks this tag is right.
Removed. It is the paragraph following 030L.

```suggestion
@[stacks 09HJ "The definition of both side in 09HJ is exactly the same as in this lemma."]
```
Or maybe "`sepDegree` is defined as the right hand side of 09HJ"
Thanks. Fixed.
I don't think this tag is right.

09HR writes:
Let E/F be an extension of fields. Then Aut(E/F) or AutF(E) denotes the automorphism group of E as an object of the category of F-extensions. Elements of Aut(E/F) are called automorphisms of E over F or automorphisms of E/F.

In mathlib, we do use `AlgEquiv` for Aut(E/F)?

I added a comment 
"This generalize beyond the field case in 09HR. In mathlib, we use `AlgEquiv` to denote Aut(E/F)."

`AlgEquiv` is more than `Aut(E/F)`.  
I think this tag should be moved to the group instance on `AlgEquiv F E E`.
Yes. I'll do it.
Fixed.
Note that we don't require char K = p here.
Thanks! Added in the comments.
I think this comment needs to be amended (or removed)
Thanks! I'll remove the comments.
I was confused at first. Maybe tag `IsAlgClosed` with `09GR` saying that we are using (4) as the official def instead?
Yes! That's a good idea. Added.

Also modified the tags before `IntermediateField.eq_bot_of_isAlgClosed_of_isAlgebraic` to @[stacks 09GQ "The result is the definition of algebraically closedness in Stacks Project. \
This statement is 09GR (4)  (1)."]
I don't understand why this string isn't just a doc-string.
Oh, I think this should be modified to "First part. We don't require p to be a prime in mathlib."

09FS is 
The characteristic of Fp is p, and that of Q is 0.

This is the copy of the first half of the sentence.
Fixed two 09FS tags.
